Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and chopped into roughly ½cm pieces). Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve, then remove the core from the @yellow pepper{1}(halved and chopped into 1cm chunks). Drain the @red kidney beans{1 can} in a #colander{} and rinse under cold running water. Roughly chop the @coriander{1 bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Put a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the @minced beef{250%g}. Cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> TIP: Heating the oil before adding the meat means the beef will fry and not stew.

Once the beef has browned, add the onion and pepper to your pan. Cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Add the garlic and @Mexican spice{1.5%tbsp} and stir everything together. Cook for ~{1%minute} more. Add the @tinned plum tomatoes{1 can} and the @beef stock pot{1/2}. Stir to make sure it's dissolved.

Add the kidney beans. Bring the mixture to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer gently until thick and tomatoey, ~{10-15%minutes}. Taste and add @salt{to taste} and @black pepper{to taste} if necessary.

Meanwhile, spread the @super soft tortillas with whole wheat{2} in a single layer on a lightly oiled #baking tray{}. Drizzle over a little more @oil{drizzle} and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Pop them on the top shelf of your oven and bake for ~{3-5%minutes}. Keep an eye out - you want them to be golden and crispy but not burnt! Once cooked, remove from your oven and lay on some #kitchen paper{} to absorb any excess oil.

Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g}. Slice the @avocado{1} in half vertically and twist apart. Remove the stone and scoop the flesh into a #small bowl{}. Add most of the coriander, a good squeeze of @lime{1/2}(juiced) and a generous pinch of @salt{pinch}. Mash with a #fork{}. You've just made guacamole! Lay one tortilla on each plate, pile it high with beef, sprinkle on the cheese and remaining coriander and finish with a dollop of guacamole. Tuck in!

> Tostadas are simply toasted tortillas. It makes them deliciously crispy! We've given you more tortillas here than you need for the recipe and we hate the thought of them going to waste. Why not make your own tortilla chips with what's left? Just cut them into triangles, drizzle with oil and season with salt, black pepper and any other spices you fancy before baking in the oven until crunchy. Enjoy!